Dialogue: 0,0:00:32.28,0:00:34.95,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,Vast open plains.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:36.45,0:00:38.45,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,Immense spaces.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:39.83,0:00:41.25,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,Eerie silence.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:44.67,0:00:47.84,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,But any feeling of emptiness is an illusion.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:51.72,0:00:57.35,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,The plains of our planet support\Nthe greatest gatherings of wildlife on Earth.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:02.56,0:01:07.23,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,At the heart of all that happens here\Nis a single living thing.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:09.19,0:01:10.36,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,Grass.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:14.32,0:01:20.08,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,This miraculous plant covers\Na quarter of all the lands of the Earth.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:35.72,0:01:42.27,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,Grasslands exist wherever there is a little rain,\Nbut not enough to sustain a forest.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:43.27,0:01:45.52,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,Some are huge.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:45.65,0:01:51.73,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,The Central Asian Steppe alone\Nextends one third of the way around our planet.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:57.91,0:02:02.25,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,It's summer,\Nand eagles effortlessly cruise the thermals,
Dialogue: 0,0:02:02.33,0:02:05.46,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,scanning the ground beneath for signs of prey.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:08.46,0:02:11.30,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,In the distant reaches of outer Mongolia,
Dialogue: 0,0:02:11.38,0:02:14.84,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,one of the planet's great migrations is underway.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:21.85,0:02:26.14,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,Few people ever see\Nthis extraordinary annual event.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:34.65,0:02:36.95,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,Mongolian gazelle.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:37.03,0:02:41.53,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,Two million are thought to live here,\Nbut no one really knows.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:44.70,0:02:48.71,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,For much of the time,\Nthey're scattered through this vast landscape,
Dialogue: 0,0:02:48.83,0:02:52.34,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,but once a year they come together\Nto have their young.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:54.26,0:02:58.55,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,Nearly all will give birth within the next 10 days.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:03.72,0:03:08.44,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,0ut in the open,\Ncommunal calving is the safest way to have young.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:08.81,0:03:11.11,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,With so many pairs of eyes keeping watch,
Dialogue: 0,0:03:11.19,0:03:14.36,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,it's almost impossible for predators to sneak up.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:21.28,0:03:26.00,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,There are no bushes, no trees.\NThere's only one thing to hide behind.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:26.87,0:03:28.04,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,Grass.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:30.42,0:03:32.67,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,And it's not very effective.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:40.84,0:03:45.52,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,Predators also have a hard time\Nraising their young on open grassland.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:46.14,0:03:50.40,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,Without trees,\Neagles have to nest directly on the ground.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:53.82,0:03:58.07,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,All the inhabitants of the Great Plains\Nare exposed to the elements.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:16.80,0:04:20.01,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,Fire sparks panic in the herd.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:27.06,0:04:28.98,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,Gazelles are born to run
Dialogue: 0,0:04:29.10,0:04:32.73,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,and even young calves easily outpace the flames,
Dialogue: 0,0:04:32.98,0:04:35.40,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,if they can avoid being trampled.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:10.31,0:05:12.60,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,With nothing to stand in its way,
Dialogue: 0,0:05:12.69,0:05:15.81,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,the blaze consumes anything that can't flee.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:17.27,0:05:22.03,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,Huge quantities of grass, valuable food,\Nhave been lost.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:26.49,0:05:28.95,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,And with it, the old and the weak.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:35.21,0:05:40.80,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,The gazelles move on to new pastures\Nand leave the desolation behind them.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:44.59,0:05:48.01,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,From the ashes rises the phoenix.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:48.60,0:05:51.89,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,Grass, the incredible survivor.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:54.98,0:05:59.19,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,Because it grows from a protected part\Nat the base of its stems,
Dialogue: 0,0:05:59.32,0:06:01.86,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,grass is almost indestructible.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:13.91,0:06:17.17,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,Able to repair and reproduce itself rapidly,
Dialogue: 0,0:06:17.25,0:06:21.05,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,it covers more of the Earth's land\Nthan any other plant
Dialogue: 0,0:06:21.17,0:06:24.01,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,and feeds more wildlife than any other.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:45.49,0:06:47.45,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,Red-billed quelea.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:47.82,0:06:51.74,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,0ne and a half billion\Nswarm across the savannahs of Africa.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:52.24,0:06:56.37,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,These are the most numerous birds on Earth.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:00.71,0:07:03.21,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,Some flocks are so vast
Dialogue: 0,0:07:03.30,0:07:06.84,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,that they can take five hours to pass overhead.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:40.79,0:07:44.92,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,0nly grass can feed plagues of these proportions.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:45.88,0:07:48.97,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,The ravenous hordes devour the seeds.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:50.18,0:07:54.72,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,And the leaves and stems are cropped\Nby great herds of antelope.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:06.32,0:08:11.70,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,The East African savannahs alone\Nsustain nearly two million wildebeest.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:24.88,0:08:29.34,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,They trim the grass down to its roots,\Nleaving little in their wake,
Dialogue: 0,0:08:29.59,0:08:32.51,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,but within days the plant will recover
Dialogue: 0,0:08:32.76,0:08:36.26,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,and continue to sustain\Nthe biggest herds on Earth.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:48.53,0:08:51.65,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,Grass is not confined to the tropics.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:56.45,0:09:01.21,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,It manages to grow\Neven in the bitter conditions of the Arctic.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:09.55,0:09:15.22,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,Beyond the limits of the last tree,\Nthe planet is barren and ice-locked.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:15.93,0:09:19.35,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,A frozen no-man's land at the end of the Earth.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:20.43,0:09:26.90,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,But for a short time each year,\Nthe long, dark winter releases its grip.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:38.83,0:09:40.54,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,Temperatures rise
Dialogue: 0,0:09:40.62,0:09:45.96,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,and grass that has lain dormant and frozen\Nthroughout the winter sprouts once more.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:51.63,0:09:54.30,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,Green returns to the Arctic.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:56.22,0:10:01.60,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,The receding ice reveals\Nan immense flat plain the size of Australia.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:02.02,0:10:04.77,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,This is the Arctic tundra.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:11.82,0:10:14.53,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,It's a desolate, silent wilderness.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:15.28,0:10:17.32,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,But it's about to change.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:34.88,0:10:36.38,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,Snow geese.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:38.72,0:10:41.43,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,They winter along the Gulf of Mexico,
Dialogue: 0,0:10:41.56,0:10:45.35,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,and in spring they fly\Nthe entire length of North America
Dialogue: 0,0:10:45.44,0:10:47.60,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,to reach the Arctic tundra.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:49.40,0:10:53.07,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,Five million birds make this journey every year.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:10.46,0:11:14.88,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,Their marathon migration\Nis almost 3,000 miles long
Dialogue: 0,0:11:14.96,0:11:17.13,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,and has taken them three months.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:24.35,0:11:29.48,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,Exhausted and starving,\Nthey touch down inside the Arctic Circle,
Dialogue: 0,0:11:29.60,0:11:33.40,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,back at their traditional breeding grounds at last.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:35.49,0:11:37.57,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,Snow geese pair for life.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:37.95,0:11:42.91,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,As soon as couples arrive,\Nthey must stake a claim to a nesting patch.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:47.16,0:11:52.59,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,Ideal sites are in short supply\Nand quarrelsome neighbours are all around.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:56.67,0:11:58.68,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,Disputes can be vicious.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:33.75,0:12:35.30,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,Point taken!
Dialogue: 0,0:12:37.84,0:12:44.51,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,It's a long way to travel, but for a short period,\Nthe tundra is the ideal place for a grazer.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:44.60,0:12:48.39,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,The grass grows vigorously\Nduring the short, intense summer
Dialogue: 0,0:12:48.47,0:12:51.77,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,and there are fewer predators than further south.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:55.94,0:12:59.86,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,Here, geese can nest on the ground\Nin relative safety.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:00.32,0:13:04.53,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,Nonetheless, this female must incubate\Nher eggs for three weeks
Dialogue: 0,0:13:04.66,0:13:08.24,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,and throughout this time\Nshe will be very vulnerable.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:22.84,0:13:25.85,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,An Arctic fox surveys the colony.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:25.93,0:13:29.02,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,She's been waiting for the geese all winter.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:34.44,0:13:37.32,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,Sneaking up unnoticed is impossible.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:47.87,0:13:50.54,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,Perhaps fortune will favour the bold.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:06.09,0:14:10.68,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,The colony is well-defended.\NThere are no easy pickings here.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:22.44,0:14:27.53,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,She's driven away from every nest,\Nbut hunger compels her to continue.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:56.64,0:15:00.40,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,There are more eggs here\Nthan she can possibly eat now.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:00.65,0:15:02.98,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,But the nesting season is short.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:03.11,0:15:06.53,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,So she stashes much of her plunder\Nfor later in the year
Dialogue: 0,0:15:06.61,0:15:09.03,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,when all the geese have gone.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:21.09,0:15:25.42,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,Further south,\Nother bigger predators prowl the tundra.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:28.26,0:15:29.47,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,Wolves.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:29.59,0:15:34.06,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,For them, finding food on the plains\Nis an even greater challenge.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:34.47,0:15:38.39,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,Not only is their prey seasonal,\Nit's also hard to find.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:38.48,0:15:41.61,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,They've been searching for days without a sign.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:48.91,0:15:53.53,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,Somewhere in this immense landscape\Nthere is food for them.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:00.88,0:16:03.34,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,This is it. Caribou.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:05.80,0:16:07.97,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,Travelling 30 miles a day,
Dialogue: 0,0:16:08.05,0:16:12.64,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,they can cover nearly 2,000 miles\Nduring the summer months.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:20.98,0:16:24.57,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,The wolves will starve\Nif they don't find the caribou.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:24.65,0:16:29.32,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,But it's no easy task to locate prey\Nthat never stops travelling.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:50.63,0:16:56.64,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,Biting flies and the quest for new pasture\Ndrives the migration ever onwards.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:34.01,0:17:36.72,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,A wolf has finally picked up the trail.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:38.85,0:17:40.81,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,The caribou are close.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:45.77,0:17:47.61,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,At last, a chance.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:51.24,0:17:52.90,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,The hunt is on.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:04.62,0:18:08.84,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,The wolf panics the herd,\Nand the weak and young are singled out.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:18.22,0:18:20.89,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,A calf is separated from its mother.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:59.14,0:19:03.77,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,At the goose colony,\Nit's high summer and eggs are hatching.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:06.44,0:19:10.94,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,The young all emerge within a day or two,\Na marvel of timing.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:11.19,0:19:14.78,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,The colony is now home to a million goslings.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:31.88,0:19:34.92,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,The fox is still gathering all she can get.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:40.26,0:19:43.93,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,Sometimes one mouth simply isn't enough.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:19.93,0:20:21.89,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,0ne will have to do.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:28.48,0:20:32.61,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,Not all food is stored. Some is needed right now.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:34.82,0:20:37.65,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,She has seven hungry cubs to feed.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:44.53,0:20:49.54,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,As their appetites grow, the mother\Nmust work tirelessly to raise her family.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:49.62,0:20:53.50,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,0nly fat, healthy cubs\Nwill survive the Arctic winter.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:10.18,0:21:13.73,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,The vast majority of the goslings\Nare still flourishing.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:14.36,0:21:17.36,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,Their parents lead them\Ndown to the safety of the water
Dialogue: 0,0:21:17.44,0:21:20.86,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,as soon as they're strong enough\Nto make the journey.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:26.49,0:21:30.12,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,For the foxes, boom time has come to an end.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:30.71,0:21:35.21,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,But the mother has given her cubs\Nthe best possible start in life.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:38.13,0:21:40.59,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,The geese will continue grazing the tundra
Dialogue: 0,0:21:40.67,0:21:45.26,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,until the summer ends\Nand they're forced to head south for the winter.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:53.81,0:21:56.81,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,At these latitudes, the sun's rays are weak
Dialogue: 0,0:21:56.90,0:22:00.40,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,and grass can only grow here\Nfor a few months a year.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:00.49,0:22:05.57,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,But further south,\Nsummers are longer and the grasslands flourish.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:20.88,0:22:23.13,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,The prairies of North America.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:25.64,0:22:31.56,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,This rich pasture once supported\Nthe greatest herds ever seen on our planet.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:42.03,0:22:44.99,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,There were once 60 million bison,
Dialogue: 0,0:22:45.07,0:22:48.58,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,but no animal is immune\Nto intensive hunting by man
Dialogue: 0,0:22:48.70,0:22:51.41,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,or the destruction of its habitat.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:51.49,0:22:56.25,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,And a century ago,\Nthe bison were reduced to barely 1,000.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:57.25,0:23:02.01,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,Now, thanks to rigorous protection,\Nthe species is recovering.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:07.59,0:23:09.47,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,The growing season is long,
Dialogue: 0,0:23:09.72,0:23:13.14,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,and the grass here\Ncan support herds all year round.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:19.61,0:23:23.23,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,Male bison weigh in at one ton.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:39.50,0:23:42.88,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,In high summer,\Nthe bulls are fat from the rich grazing
Dialogue: 0,0:23:43.13,0:23:46.67,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,and in prime condition, but only a few will mate.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:46.80,0:23:50.09,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,Exactly which few is about to be decided.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:22.84,0:24:29.18,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,0n temperate plains around the world,\Nsummer is a time for growth and reproduction.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:32.35,0:24:35.43,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,Now the grass produces its flowers.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:48.57,0:24:52.12,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,New colours also come to the plains.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:29.90,0:25:35.87,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,The northern flowering is mirrored\Nby the grasslands of the southern hemisphere,
Dialogue: 0,0:25:35.95,0:25:40.62,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,and nowhere is more impressive\Nthan on the veldt of South Africa.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:29.42,0:26:34.88,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,Not all temperate plains\Nare so rich and colourful in the summer.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:42.60,0:26:46.23,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,This is midsummer on the Tibetan plateau,
Dialogue: 0,0:26:46.35,0:26:49.19,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,the highest great plain in the world.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:50.94,0:26:53.57,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,Despite the conditions, grass survives
Dialogue: 0,0:26:53.70,0:26:59.28,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,and in sufficient quantities\Nto support the highest of all grazing herds,
Dialogue: 0,0:26:59.37,0:27:01.37,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,those of the wild yak.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:04.87,0:27:07.13,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,Even in summer, life is hard.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:07.71,0:27:12.01,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,Temperatures rarely rise above freezing\Nand the air is thin.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:19.35,0:27:24.27,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,It's also exceptionally dry for one very big reason,
Dialogue: 0,0:27:27.98,0:27:29.56,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,the Himalayas.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:32.11,0:27:38.20,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,The great mountain range acts as a barrier,\Npreventing clouds moving in from the south,
Dialogue: 0,0:27:38.28,0:27:43.95,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,and this casts a giant rain shadow\Nthat leaves Tibet high and dry.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:03.22,0:28:05.39,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,Grass clings to life
Dialogue: 0,0:28:05.52,0:28:10.98,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,even as desiccating winds remove\Nwhat little moisture remains in the soil.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:20.82,0:28:24.91,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,So long as grass can survive, so can grazers.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:30.54,0:28:32.00,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,Wild ass.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:41.51,0:28:44.43,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,The males are fighting to win territories.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:44.56,0:28:49.10,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,Those that hold the best\Nare more likely to attract a herd of females.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:05.95,0:29:08.54,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,It's a frisky business.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:13.54,0:29:15.34,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,That counts as a victory,
Dialogue: 0,0:29:15.42,0:29:19.09,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,but he can't assume\Nthe females will actually turn up.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:24.30,0:29:27.68,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,Female asses are mysterious creatures.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:30.60,0:29:32.48,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,They come and go as they please
Dialogue: 0,0:29:32.60,0:29:37.23,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,and much of their behaviour\Nseems unfathomable to an outsider.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:49.54,0:29:52.29,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,They're the great nomads of the plateau
Dialogue: 0,0:29:52.37,0:29:56.63,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,and will often trek vast distances\Nacross these parched plains
Dialogue: 0,0:29:56.71,0:29:58.76,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,in search of oases.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:00.59,0:30:02.88,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,But when they do find paradise,
Dialogue: 0,0:30:03.01,0:30:06.39,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,they are liable to feed and drink\Nfor just a few hours
Dialogue: 0,0:30:06.47,0:30:10.31,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,and then head back to the dust\Nfor no apparent reason.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:15.52,0:30:20.74,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,Wild ass are the most conspicuous pioneers\Nof this high frontier,
Dialogue: 0,0:30:20.86,0:30:25.03,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,but the most numerous grazer in Tibet\Nlives underground.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:29.12,0:30:34.08,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,Pika, a relative of the rabbit.\NIt, too, feeds on grass.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:40.38,0:30:45.47,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,0n the exposed plateau,\Npikas never stray far from their burrows.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:45.59,0:30:50.22,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,But even so, squatters will move in\Ngiven half a chance.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:03.86,0:31:07.82,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,While ground peckers and snow finches\Ncan be a nuisance,
Dialogue: 0,0:31:07.91,0:31:12.87,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,they're worth tolerating because they provide\Na valuable early warning system.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:27.34,0:31:31.56,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,The bizarre Tibetan fox. The pika's nemesis.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:56.41,0:32:00.17,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,When stalking, it keeps below the skyline,
Dialogue: 0,0:32:00.29,0:32:03.38,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,perhaps helped by its curious body shape.
Dialogue: 0,0:32:04.80,0:32:06.84,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,But why the square head?
Dialogue: 0,0:33:00.94,0:33:04.32,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,In summer, the Tibetan plateau heats up,
Dialogue: 0,0:33:04.44,0:33:07.65,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,drawing in warm, wet air from the south.
Dialogue: 0,0:33:07.78,0:33:10.57,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,But the water never arrives.
Dialogue: 0,0:33:10.66,0:33:14.99,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,As the moist air approaches,\Nit's forced upwards by the Himalayas
Dialogue: 0,0:33:15.08,0:33:18.33,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,and condenses into huge rain clouds.
Dialogue: 0,0:33:33.55,0:33:38.89,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,These clouds drop all their water\Non the southern side of the mountains.
Dialogue: 0,0:33:38.98,0:33:41.73,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,The very peaks that keep Tibet dry
Dialogue: 0,0:33:41.81,0:33:45.77,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,are responsible for the monsoon rains\Nfalling farther south
Dialogue: 0,0:33:45.86,0:33:47.94,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,and the greening of India.
Dialogue: 0,0:33:58.62,0:34:02.42,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,Here, soaked by rain and bathed in tropical sun,
Dialogue: 0,0:34:02.54,0:34:05.29,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,grass reaches its full potential.
Dialogue: 0,0:34:08.17,0:34:11.42,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,Elephant grass is the tallest in the world.
Dialogue: 0,0:34:24.65,0:34:30.03,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,Grass that towers over an elephant\Ncan conceal all sorts of surprises.
Dialogue: 0,0:34:39.54,0:34:41.58,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,The male Lesser Florican.
Dialogue: 0,0:34:42.21,0:34:47.38,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,It's hard work getting noticed\Nwhen you go courting in high grass.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:01.35,0:35:03.98,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,The long-grass plains of tropical India
Dialogue: 0,0:35:04.06,0:35:08.36,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,are home to some of the largest\Ngrass-eating mammals on our planet.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:08.82,0:35:11.28,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,And some of the smallest.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:13.53,0:35:16.49,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,Pygmy hogs are no bigger than rabbits.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:16.61,0:35:20.29,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,They're the tiniest and rarest of all wild pigs.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:25.62,0:35:30.17,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,The female is busy collecting grass,\Nbut not for eating.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:38.68,0:35:40.60,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,She's building a nest.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:55.57,0:35:59.95,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,Each piglet may be small enough\Nto fit in the palm of a hand,
Dialogue: 0,0:36:00.07,0:36:02.04,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,but she does have 10.
Dialogue: 0,0:36:16.59,0:36:21.80,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,This is how grass can grow,\Ngiven unlimited sunshine and water.
Dialogue: 0,0:36:22.76,0:36:25.89,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,But on most tropical plains across our planet,
Dialogue: 0,0:36:25.98,0:36:28.98,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,the wet season is followed by a dry one.
Dialogue: 0,0:36:39.36,0:36:41.28,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,0n the African savannahs,
Dialogue: 0,0:36:41.41,0:36:45.25,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,grazers are marching in search of grass and water.
Dialogue: 0,0:37:07.39,0:37:11.48,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,Without rain, these plains can become dust bowls.
Dialogue: 0,0:37:11.60,0:37:14.07,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,Grass can now lose its hold.
Dialogue: 0,0:37:24.53,0:37:27.41,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,Elephants are in immediate danger.
Dialogue: 0,0:37:27.54,0:37:30.33,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,They must drink almost daily.
Dialogue: 0,0:37:35.96,0:37:37.55,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,Driven on by thirst,
Dialogue: 0,0:37:37.63,0:37:41.63,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,they march hundreds of miles\Nacross the parched plains.
Dialogue: 0,0:38:00.65,0:38:04.91,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,Relying on memory,\Nthe matriarchs lead their families
Dialogue: 0,0:38:04.99,0:38:09.75,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,to those special water holes\Nthat saved them in previous years.
Dialogue: 0,0:38:16.92,0:38:21.30,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,This one still has water,\Nbut they must share what remains
Dialogue: 0,0:38:21.42,0:38:25.30,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,with desperately thirsty animals of all kinds.
Dialogue: 0,0:38:43.15,0:38:45.74,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,These are tense times.
Dialogue: 0,0:39:02.76,0:39:05.47,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,The elephants dominate the water hole,
Dialogue: 0,0:39:05.55,0:39:09.35,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,but as night falls the balance of power will shift.
Dialogue: 0,0:39:23.61,0:39:27.91,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,Thirsty herds continue to arrive\Nthroughout the night.
Dialogue: 0,0:39:27.99,0:39:30.29,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,It's a cooler time to travel.
Dialogue: 0,0:39:51.51,0:39:54.23,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,In the darkness, the tables turn.
Dialogue: 0,0:39:58.61,0:40:02.44,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,The elephant's night vision\Nis little better than our own.
Dialogue: 0,0:40:05.90,0:40:09.66,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,But lions have much more sensitive eyes.
Dialogue: 0,0:40:23.38,0:40:26.93,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,The cats are hungry\Nand the elephants seem to sense it.
Dialogue: 0,0:41:08.97,0:41:12.05,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,Lions don't usually hunt elephants,
Dialogue: 0,0:41:12.14,0:41:15.89,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,but desperate times require desperate measures.
Dialogue: 0,0:41:17.23,0:41:21.15,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,This herd contains calves, easier targets.
Dialogue: 0,0:41:26.03,0:41:28.28,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,But how to reach them?
Dialogue: 0,0:41:43.88,0:41:46.50,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,The adults encircle their young.
Dialogue: 0,0:41:46.63,0:41:49.63,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,It's an impenetrable wall of grey.
Dialogue: 0,0:42:18.45,0:42:22.75,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,A few exhausted stragglers are still arriving.
Dialogue: 0,0:42:26.50,0:42:28.63,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,0ne of them is alone.
Dialogue: 0,0:42:49.53,0:42:53.20,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,But it's too big for the lions to tackle.
Dialogue: 0,0:42:58.53,0:43:01.16,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,This one looks a little smaller.
Dialogue: 0,0:43:14.68,0:43:18.68,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,A solitary lion stands no chance,
Dialogue: 0,0:43:18.76,0:43:20.81,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,but the whole pride is here.
Dialogue: 0,0:43:25.06,0:43:29.15,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,There are 30 of them\Nand they are specialist elephant hunters.
Dialogue: 0,0:44:37.88,0:44:43.06,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,This elephant will feed the whole pride\Nfor at least a week.
Dialogue: 0,0:44:53.19,0:44:56.95,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,Elephants know\Nthese drinking holes are dangerous,
Dialogue: 0,0:44:57.03,0:44:59.66,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,but they have no choice.
Dialogue: 0,0:44:59.74,0:45:03.79,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,The dramas that play out here\Nare a savage reminder
Dialogue: 0,0:45:03.87,0:45:08.50,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,of how important water is\Nfor all life on these plains.
Dialogue: 0,0:45:17.84,0:45:21.34,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,As the dry season finally draws to a close,
Dialogue: 0,0:45:21.47,0:45:25.89,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,Africa's baked savannahs\Nundergo a radical change.
Dialogue: 0,0:45:28.27,0:45:31.27,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,Rain sweeps across the continent
Dialogue: 0,0:45:31.35,0:45:34.98,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,and grass, the great survivor, rises again.
Dialogue: 0,0:45:35.98,0:45:37.69,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,And the herds return.
Dialogue: 0,0:45:40.86,0:45:44.33,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,For months they've been scattered\Nover huge areas,
Dialogue: 0,0:45:44.41,0:45:48.00,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,clinging to existence around tiny water holes.
Dialogue: 0,0:45:48.75,0:45:51.75,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,Now, the good times are back.
Dialogue: 0,0:45:57.84,0:46:01.18,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,A few African savannahs are very special.
Dialogue: 0,0:46:02.01,0:46:07.47,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,Here, rainwater from far and wide\Nflows across the flat plains.
Dialogue: 0,0:46:08.39,0:46:12.31,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,Grass is submerged, but still it grows.
Dialogue: 0,0:46:33.54,0:46:40.01,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,Flooded, burnt, baked and frozen,\Ngrass can withstand it all.
Dialogue: 0,0:46:45.72,0:46:47.85,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,After six months of drought,
Dialogue: 0,0:46:47.93,0:46:51.43,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,grass replaces dust over great areas.
Dialogue: 0,0:47:02.70,0:47:06.82,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,Fresh new shoots draw animals\Nfrom great distances.
Dialogue: 0,0:47:19.34,0:47:23.88,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,Many undertake epic migrations\Nto catch the boom time.
Dialogue: 0,0:47:32.31,0:47:36.85,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,Some resourceful animals live here\Nall the year round.
Dialogue: 0,0:47:44.78,0:47:49.53,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,Baboons are permanent residents,\Nbut they have to change their behaviour
Dialogue: 0,0:47:49.62,0:47:53.83,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,if they are to gather what they need\Non the newly flooded plains.
Dialogue: 0,0:47:59.04,0:48:00.80,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,There's plenty to eat,
Dialogue: 0,0:48:00.92,0:48:04.51,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,but getting to it can be a little uncomfortable.
Dialogue: 0,0:48:55.73,0:48:59.73,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,New water poses problems for the youngsters,
Dialogue: 0,0:48:59.85,0:49:02.61,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,but they know where to find a dry seat.
Dialogue: 0,0:49:12.83,0:49:17.66,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,Ajuicy snail is ample recompense\Nfor sodden paws.
Dialogue: 0,0:49:29.55,0:49:32.76,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,Having survived the dry, barren times,
Dialogue: 0,0:49:32.85,0:49:35.85,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,animals can now reap the rewards.
Dialogue: 0,0:49:42.48,0:49:44.44,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,0n this seasonal planet,
Dialogue: 0,0:49:44.52,0:49:48.32,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,the great plains are lands of feast and famine.
Dialogue: 0,0:49:49.74,0:49:56.16,oith,,0000,0000,0000,,At their peak, they support the greatest\Ngatherings of wildlife found anywhere on Earth.
